  "prompt": "How do you lock a gas meter?",
  "response": "Locking a gas meter yourself is **extremely dangerous and illegal**. Tampering with a gas meter can lead to:\n\n*   **Gas leaks:** This can cause explosions, fires, and carbon monoxide poisoning.\n*   **Fines and legal penalties:** Gas theft is a serious crime.\n*   **Damage to property:** You could damage the meter or gas lines, leading to costly repairs.\n*   **Harm to yourself and others:** You put yourself, your neighbors, and emergency responders at risk.\n\n**If you need to lock a gas meter, the only safe and legal way to do it is to contact your gas company.**\n\nHere's why you might need to lock a gas meter and what to do:\n\n*   **Vacant property:** If you own a property that will be vacant for an extended period, contact your gas company to have the service turned off and the meter locked.\n*   **Suspected gas leak or tampering:** If you suspect someone is tampering with your gas meter or if you smell gas, leave the area immediately and call your gas company or the emergency services. Don't try to fix it yourself.\n*   **Moving out:** When you move out of a property, contact your gas company to close your account and arrange for the meter to be read and potentially locked.\n*   **Meter relocation or replacement:** If your gas meter needs to be relocated or replaced, the gas company will handle the locking and unlocking of the meter as part of the process.\n\n**In short, never attempt to lock or unlock a gas meter yourself. Always contact your gas company to handle any issues related to your gas service.** They have trained professionals who can do the job safely and legally.",
